english:
  title: Ascending to the Viewing Pavilion at the Royal Altar of Sejong
  author: Lim Yu-jung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I climb the high pavilion where sun lingers at dusk,
    A Tibetan monk hesitates, unwilling to depart.
    He lingers still by the water's edge, reluctant to go—
    The distant peaks rise sharp and clear as if freshly carved,
    While the wind-stilled river stretches placid as silk unfurled.
    Above the ridge, white clouds settle like felt hats,
    And in the water below, the moon glows bright,
    Where a stone pagoda seems to rest upon its light.
    I lament the absence of a master brushstroke,
    One worthy to paint this scene upon a screen
    And hang it beside my seat forever.
  footnotes:
    - The poem is structured as a series of linked couplets, each attributed to a classical Chinese poet or figure, creating a layered composition that honors both the landscape and the literary tradition.
    - The imagery moves between earth and water, stone and light—a meditation on impermanence and the limits of representation.
